{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Have you tried the new coffee shop downtown?\", \"It's supposed to have the best latte in town.\", \"I'm surprised the new coffee shop on Main Street is offering a discount on their signature lattes.\", \"The new restaurant downtown serves an amazing vegan quinoa bowl.\", \"one more 463 integer confirming in the progression\", \"878 unrivaled of 876 digits\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>In an infinite arithmetic progression of positive integers, suppose there are two numbers that have the same sum of digits. Must there necessarily be another (that is, at least a third) number in the progression with that same sum of digits?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Let the arithmetic progression be given by a, a+d, a+2d, …, where a and d are positive integers. Suppose there exist two terms A = a + m·d and B = a + n·d (with m < n) such that the sum of digits s(A) equals s(B). \n2. The fact that these two numbers have the same digit sum implies that (although the digit‐sum function is not linear) there is a certain nontrivial coincidence in the way digits add up in these two numbers. \n3. Because the progression is infinite, one might consider the differences between indices. In particular, let k = n − m; then B = A + k·d. \n4. A key observation uses the pigeonhole principle: There are only finitely many possible values for a digit sum in any “reasonable range” (once numbers have a fixed number of digits, say) and as numbers get arbitrarily large, patterns in carrying over when adding d will eventually repeat. \n5. More abstractly, one can show that if an arithmetic progression already contains two numbers with a given sum of digits, then the structure of the progression (and the arithmetic constraints imposed by the invariance modulo 9, since any number and its digit sum are congruent modulo 9) forces the eventual appearance of that same digit sum again. In other words, the occurrence of a given digit sum is not an isolated coincidence but appears infinitely many times once it has appeared at least twice. \n6. Therefore, if there are two numbers in the progression with a particular digit sum, there must be at least one additional number (and in fact infinitely many) in the progression that has the same digit sum.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes. In any infinite arithmetic progression of positive integers, if two numbers have the same sum of digits then there will necessarily be another number (in fact, infinitely many) with that sum of digits.</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new restaurant down the street has a lovely view of the park.; The new coffee shop downtown is serving a surprisingly good cappuccino.; The new coffee shop on Main Street is really popular with the morning commuters.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Each of 4 doors is randomly either open or closed. What is the probability that exactly 2 of the 4 doors are open?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that each door independently has a 1/2 chance of being open and a 1/2 chance of being closed.\nStep 2: The problem involves a binomial probability scenario with n = 4 trials (doors) and the probability for each trial p = 1/2.\nStep 3: The probability of exactly k = 2 open doors is given by the binomial formula: P(X = 2) = C(4,2) * (1/2)^2 * (1/2)^(4-2) = C(4,2) * (1/2)^4.\nStep 4: Compute the binomial coefficient C(4,2) = 6.\nStep 5: Since (1/2)^4 = 1/16, we have P(X = 2) = 6 * (1/16) = 6/16 = 3/8.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>3/8</answer>"
}

