  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The weather forecast for next week is looking quite unpredictable.; The new restaurant downtown has a great selection of vegan options.; The new food truck on the corner has amazing empanadas.; The phrases '574 crinkle', 'pedigree', 'x , okay', '876', and '878' are noise.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Given the line with equation y = 2x - 6, which is translated upward by 4 units, what is the x-intercept of the resulting line?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Understand that translating a line upward by 4 units means adding 4 to the y-value of every point on the line. Thus, the equation y = 2x - 6 becomes y = 2x - 6 + 4, which simplifies to y = 2x - 2. Step 2: To find the x-intercept of a line, set y equal to 0 and solve for x. Step 3: Set 0 = 2x - 2 and solve: 2x - 2 = 0 => 2x = 2 => x = 1.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The weather in Paris is quite lovely this time of year, don't you think?; The new coffee shop downtown has an amazing selection of artisanal teas.; Have you tried that new coffee shop downtown?</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find the unique odd integer N between 400 and 600 that is divisible by both 5 and 11. What is the sum of the digits of N?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Since N is divisible by both 5 and 11, it must be divisible by the least common multiple of 5 and 11, which is 55.\\n2. Find the multiples of 55 between 400 and 600: 55×8=440, 55×9=495, and 55×10=550.\\n3. Identify the odd integer among these: 440 is even, 495 is odd, and 550 is even. Thus, N=495.\\n4. Calculate the sum of the digits of 495: 4+9+5=18.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>18</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentences mentioning '521', '878', '876 [ i ]', 'the new coffee shop downtown has the most amazing lavender lattes, have you tried one yet?', 'Did you hear that the new restaurant downtown has an amazing brunch buffet?', and 'Have you tried the new cafe down the street, I heard their coffee is excellent?' are not needed to solve the problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let n > 1 be a positive integer. Ana and Bob play a game with n people arranged in a circle. Bob places either a black or white hat on each person’s head. Each person can see all the hats except their own and must individually guess the color of their own hat according to a common strategy announced by Ana. Ana wants to maximize the number of correct guesses while Bob wants to minimize them. Assuming both play optimally, how many correct guesses can Ana guarantee?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that this is a variation of a well-known hat guessing puzzle where each person sees the hats of others and follows a predetermined strategy. One common optimal strategy is based on parity. \nStep 2: In the parity strategy, one designated person (say, the first person) announces a guess that encodes the parity (even or odd) of a particular hat color observed among the other players. This sacrifice may result in that person guessing incorrectly. \nStep 3: All the other n - 1 players use the announced parity, together with the hats they observe, to deduce with certainty the color of their own hat. \nStep 4: Hence, regardless of Bob's adversarial arrangement, by following this strategy Ana can guarantee that at least n - 1 people guess correctly.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>n - 1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new restaurant downtown has an amazing vegan menu.\", \"The new artisanal coffee shop in town has a lovely patio area perfect for meeting friends on a sunny afternoon.\", \"Did you hear that the new coffee shop downtown is offering a loyalty program to its frequent customers?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>An airline operates flights between any two capital cities in the European Union. For any given city, the flights departing that city have pairwise distinct prices and the cost is the same in both directions. Anna and Bella wish to visit each city exactly once (they may start in different cities). At every step, Anna always chooses the cheapest available flight from her current city to a city she has not visited yet, while Bella always takes the most expensive available flight from her current city. Is it true that Bella’s tour will surely cost at least as much as Anna’s tour?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Note that every city (except the last in the tour) is departed from exactly once. At the moment a traveler is at a city, the set of available flights (to still unvisited cities) has flight prices that are pairwise distinct. Thus, from that city there is a unique cheapest flight and a unique most expensive flight, with the most expensive flight having a cost not less than the cost of the cheapest one.\n2. Anna’s strategy is to choose the cheapest flight among those available from her current city. Bella’s strategy is to choose the most expensive flight from her current city. Although the two travelers may follow different routes (since their choices affect which cities remain unvisited), every time a decision is made from a given city the cost chosen by Bella is at least as high as the cost chosen by Anna, because the set of available flight costs at that moment (being the same for any departure from that city) satisfies: minimum ≤ maximum.\n3. Summing over all flights used (each tour uses exactly (number of cities − 1) flights), the total cost for Bella is the sum of one flight chosen as the maximum from some available set in each step, while Anna’s total is the sum of the corresponding minimums (though from possibly different sets, the key point is that in any departure, the maximum cost available is never lower than the minimum cost available).\n4. Therefore, no matter what the order of cities is, Bella’s overall tour cost will be at least as high as Anna’s overall tour cost.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, Bella’s tour will surely cost at least as much as Anna’s tour.</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new pizza place downtown has the most amazing vegan options, I heard.; Did you know that I've been planning a beach vacation for the last three weeks and I'm really excited to finally relax on the sand and listen to the sound of the waves.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>How many interior intersection points are there in a 12 by 12 grid of squares?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "A 12 by 12 grid of squares is defined by 13 points along each side (because each square contributes an extra boundary). This gives a total of 13 x 13 = 169 intersection points. These include both boundary and interior points. The interior points are those that are not on the boundary. Since the grid has 13 points per side, the boundary consists of the outermost rows and columns, leaving (13 - 2) = 11 interior points in each direction. Therefore, the number of interior intersection points is 11 x 11 = 121.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>121</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The weather in Paris is quite chilly during the winter months.\", \"Did you hear that the new restaurant downtown has an amazing brunch menu?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find the largest integer n less than 2012 such that every divisor of n has at most two 1's in its binary representation.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Note that since n is a divisor of itself, n must have at most two 1's in its binary representation. Thus n must be either a power of 2 (which in binary has exactly one 1) or the sum of two distinct powers of 2 (which in binary has exactly two 1's).\n2. All divisors of n must also have this property. For numbers of the form n = 2^a, all divisors are powers of 2 and clearly have just one 1 in binary. For numbers of the form n = 2^a + 2^b (with a > b), if n has only two prime factors then its divisors are either of the form 2^k or 3×2^k (if an extra odd factor 3 appears). The binary representation of any power of 2 is fine, and a number of form 3×2^k is simply the binary number 11 followed by k zeros, having exactly two 1's.\n3. Since we need the largest integer n < 2012 that meets the condition, we examine the candidates in S (= {powers of 2} ∪ {sums of two distinct powers of 2}). The highest power of 2 less than 2012 is 1024. However, among sums of two distinct powers of 2, the largest is obtained by taking the two highest allowed powers. Since 2^10 = 1024 is the highest power less than 2012 and 2^9 = 512 is the next highest, the number n = 1024 + 512 = 1536 is in S and is less than 2012.\n4. Check divisors of 1536. Its prime factorization is 1536 = 2^9 × 3. Its divisors are of the form 2^k and 3×2^k for 0 ≤ k ≤ 9. Each 2^k is a power of 2 (one 1 in binary) and each 3×2^k has a binary representation of '11' followed by k zeros (exactly two 1's). Therefore every divisor of 1536 meets the condition.\n5. There is no candidate in S between 1536 and 2012 because any sum of two powers of 2 with the largest term 1024 and another power would be at most 1536 (since 1024 + the next largest power 512 = 1536). Thus, 1536 is the largest number less than 2012 with the desired property.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1536</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Did you hear that the new restaurant downtown is offering a buy-one-get-one-free deal on their famous buffalo wings on Fridays?\", \"My favorite way to relax on a Sunday afternoon is to watch the clouds drifting lazily by while listening to jazz music.\", \"theorize Pearl . wants ,\", \"947 chip cookies\", \"463 fleck 887\", \"the weather forecast for this weekend is expected to be partly cloudy with a high chance of fleecy clouds.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Suppose there are 100 cookies arranged in a circle, and 53 of them are chocolate chip with the remainder being oatmeal. Pearl wants to choose a contiguous subsegment of exactly 67 cookies that has exactly k chocolate chip cookies. Find the sum of all such k for which Pearl is guaranteed to be able to find such a subsegment regardless of how the cookies are arranged.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Let the cookies be arranged in a circle as a sequence of 100 elements, where 1 represents a chocolate chip cookie and 0 represents an oatmeal cookie. There are 53 ones in total. Pearl is to choose a block of 67 consecutive cookies. \n2. A known fact in problems of this type is that regardless of the arrangement, the number of ones (i.e. chocolate chip cookies) in any contiguous block of length L (here L=67) must take on all integer values in a certain interval. Specifically, the possible counts are exactly the integers from L - (total cookies - total ones) to min(L, total ones). \n3. Compute the lower bound: L - (n - total ones) = 67 - (100 - 53) = 67 - 47 = 20. Compute the upper bound: min(67, 53) = 53. \n4. Therefore, for every arrangement, there is guaranteed to be some contiguous block of 67 cookies with any number of chocolate chip cookies k, where 20 ≤ k ≤ 53. \n5. The question asks for the sum of all such k. This sum is the sum of integers from 20 to 53. \n6. There are (53 - 20 + 1) = 34 integers in this range. The sum of an arithmetic sequence is given by (first + last)*number_of_terms/2. Thus, the sum = (20 + 53) * 34 / 2 = 73 * 17 = 1241.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1241</answer>"
}

