  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"Did you know that the new coffee shop downtown has a secret menu that only a few people know about?\", \"Did you know that there's a new coffee shop opening up downtown this weekend?\", \"I'm really looking forward to trying the new pastry shop that just opened up downtown.\", \"521\" and \"878 Hana 's 876\" parts in the phrases.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Megan and Hana raced their remote control cars for 100 m. Megan's car had an average speed of 5/4 m/s, and Hana's car finished 5 seconds before Megan's. What was the average speed of Hana's car?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Calculate Megan's time: Since distance = 100 m and speed = 5/4 m/s, time = distance/speed = 100 / (5/4) = 80 seconds.\n2. Determine Hana's time: Hana finished 5 seconds faster than Megan, so her time = 80 - 5 = 75 seconds.\n3. Calculate Hana's average speed: speed = distance/time = 100/75 = 4/3 m/s.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>4/3 m/s</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The following sentences are irrelevant: 'The new restaurant in town serves the most delicious vegan quinoa bowls.', 'The new coffee shop downtown has a great selection of vegan pastries.', 'Army of the Righteous', '463', 'rout', 'damaging', '878', 'The new coffee shop on Main St is having a grand opening sale this weekend.'</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let f(x) = x^4 + ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d be a polynomial whose roots are all negative integers. If a + b + c + d = 2009, find d.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Since all roots are negative integers, write the roots as -r, -s, -t, -u with r, s, t, u positive integers. Then f(x) factors as (x + r)(x + s)(x + t)(x + u).\nStep 2: Expanding, we see that f(1) = (1 + r)(1 + s)(1 + t)(1 + u). Also, by direct substitution into f(x), f(1) = 1 + a + b + c + d = 1 + (a + b + c + d) = 1 + 2009 = 2010.\nStep 3: So, we require that (r + 1)(s + 1)(t + 1)(u + 1) = 2010. The prime factorization of 2010 is 2 × 3 × 5 × 67. Since each r + 1 must be an integer at least 2, the only possibility is to assign the four primes to r + 1, s + 1, t + 1, and u + 1, in some order.\nStep 4: For example, take r + 1 = 2, s + 1 = 3, t + 1 = 5, u + 1 = 67, which implies r = 1, s = 2, t = 4, and u = 66.\nStep 5: The constant term d is the product of the roots taken with sign reversed (since each factor is (x + r)); hence d = r × s × t × u = 1 × 2 × 4 × 66 = 528.\n",
  "final_answer": "<answer>528</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"I'm looking forward to trying the new vegan restaurant that just opened downtown.\", \"The new boutique in town is really popular among the young professionals.\", \"The weather in Paris is notoriously unpredictable during the spring season.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Alice, Bob, and Charlie roll a 4-sided, 5-sided, and 6-sided die respectively. What is the probability that exactly two of the three rolls show the same number?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Determine the total number of outcomes. The 4-sided die has 4 outcomes, the 5-sided has 5 outcomes, and the 6-sided has 6 outcomes, so total outcomes = 4*5*6 = 120.\\n\\nStep 2: Count favorable cases where exactly two dice show the same number and the third is different. We consider the three possible pairs that can match. For a pair to match, the common number must be available on both dice in that pair.\\n\\nCase 1: Matching pair on the 4-sided and 5-sided dice.\\n- The common number must appear on both; since the 4-sided die has {1,2,3,4} and the 5-sided die has {1,2,3,4,5}, the common choices are {1,2,3,4} → 4 choices.\\n- The 6-sided die (outcomes 1-6) must show a number different from the common number: 6-1 = 5 choices.\\nTotal for Case 1 = 4 * 5 = 20.\\n\\nCase 2: Matching pair on the 4-sided and 6-sided dice.\\n- The 4-sided die has {1,2,3,4} and the 6-sided die has {1,2,3,4,5,6}, so common choices: {1,2,3,4} → 4 choices.\\n- The remaining 5-sided die must show a number different from the common number: 5-1 = 4 choices.\\nTotal for Case 2 = 4 * 4 = 16.\\n\\nCase 3: Matching pair on the 5-sided and 6-sided dice.\\n- Their common faces: 5-sided has {1,2,3,4,5} and 6-sided has {1,2,3,4,5,6}, so common choices: {1,2,3,4,5} → 5 choices.\\n- The remaining 4-sided die has outcomes {1,2,3,4}.\\n   For a given common number: If the common number is 1,2,3, or 4, then the 4-sided die must avoid that number giving 3 possibilities. If the common number is 5, note that the 4-sided die cannot roll 5 anyway, so all 4 outcomes are automatically different.\\nTotal for Case 3 = (4 choices * 3 outcomes) + (1 choice * 4 outcomes) = 12 + 4 = 16.\\n\\nStep 3: Sum the favorable outcomes: 20 + 16 + 16 = 52.\\n\\nStep 4: Compute the probability = Favorable outcomes / Total outcomes = 52/120.\\nSimplify: Divide numerator and denominator by 2 to get 26/60, then by 2 again yields 13/30.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>13/30</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"I had a really great cup of coffee this morning, it was from a new coffee shop that just opened up downtown.\", \"The new restaurant in town has an excellent selection of vegan options.\", \"The new cafe downtown has a great selection of vegan pastries.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Each unit square of a 4×4 square grid is colored with one of three colors (say red, green, or blue). Over all possible colorings of the grid, what is the maximum possible number of L‐trominoes (three‐square L-shaped figures, each being the 3 of the 4 cells in a 2×2 block) that contain exactly one square of each color?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Note that an L‐tromino is any shape obtained by taking a 2×2 block and removing one of the four cells. Thus every L–tromino is uniquely contained in a 2×2 block. In a 4×4 grid there are 3 × 3 = 9 distinct overlapping 2×2 blocks, and each 2×2 block gives rise to 4 L–trominoes (one for each cell removed); hence there are 9×4 = 36 total L–tromino placements in the grid.\n2. The property we want is that the three unit squares that form the L–tromino are colored with three distinct colors (i.e. one each of red, green, and blue). In any 2×2 block the 4 cells are colored using only three available colors. Hence one of the colors must appear twice and the other two appear once. Label the cells of a 2×2 block as: top‐left = x, top–right = y, bottom–left = z, bottom–right = w. The four possible L–trominoes are: {x,y,z}, {x,y,w}, {x,z,w}, and {y,z,w}.\n3. It is readily checked that if one color appears twice in the 2×2 block (and the other two appear once each), then exactly two of the four L–trominoes (namely, those that do not include both copies of the repeated color) will have all three colors. For example, if the block colors are R, G, B, R (placed in some order) then two of the L–tromino choices yield the set {R, G, B} while the other two include two copies of R.\n4. Thus within each 2×2 block the maximum number of L–trominoes with three distinct colors is 2. Over the whole grid there are 9 such blocks, so if one can color the grid so that every one of these blocks attains the optimum arrangement, the total number of rainbow (three-colored) L–trominoes is 9×2 = 18.\n5. A careful construction (for example, by choosing a periodic or carefully balanced coloring pattern for the entire 4×4 grid) can achieve this optimum on every 2×2 block. Therefore, 18 is the maximum number possible.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>18</answer>"
}

