{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The weather in Paris is often quite beautiful during the springtime.; The new restaurant downtown serves an amazing vegan quinoa burger.; The new restaurant in town is known for its extensive collection of vintage teapots.; The numbers 521, 878, and 876 (embedded in phrases) are irrelevant.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>If A and B are two fixed (distinct) points on a given circle (with AB not a diameter) and if XY is a variable diameter of the circle, determine the locus of the intersection of the lines AX and BY.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1. Note that A and B are fixed points on the circle, and XY is any diameter (so that X and Y are diametrically opposite points on the circle). For each choice of diameter the lines through A and X and through B and Y meet at a point P. We wish to find the locus of all such points P.\nStep 2. A classical projective–geometric property now applies. In a circle, if one draws the tangents at two fixed points A and B, then as the endpoints of a diameter vary, the intersection P of AX and BY always lies on the fixed line joining the intersection of the tangents at A and B. (Many textbooks on circle geometry include the result: Given a circle and two fixed points on it, the pencil of lines joining each fixed point with one endpoint of a variable diameter is mapped under intersection into a line – namely, the line joining the two tangents.)\nStep 3. In other words, let T be the intersection of the tangents to the circle at A and B. Then, no matter which diameter XY is chosen, the point P = AX ∩ BY lies on the fixed line through T. (It can be shown by projective techniques – e.g. by showing that the mapping from a diameter XY to the intersection point P is a projectivity and that three (or two) special positions force the image to be that line.)\nStep 4. Therefore, the locus of the point P, as the diameter XY varies over all positions, is precisely the line joining the intersection T of the tangents at A and B (and it also contains other specific ‘projectively determined’ points such as the fixed point of concurrence when the diameter degenerates, but the essential answer is that the locus is this fixed line).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>The locus of the intersection of lines AX and BY is the fixed straight line through the point T, where T is the intersection of the tangents to the circle at A and B.</answer>"
}

