{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new coffee shop downtown has a lovely view of the park.\", \"Did you hear that the new restaurant downtown has an amazing brunch selection?\", \"463\", \"574\", \"947\", \"compass point in 3-space\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>If the three points (1, a, b), (a, 2, b), and (a, b, 3) are collinear in 3‐space, what is the value of a + b?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Let the points be P = (1, a, b), Q = (a, 2, b) and R = (a, b, 3). For collinearity, the vector PQ must be parallel to PR. Compute these vectors:\\n\\nPQ = Q - P = (a - 1, 2 - a, b - b) = (a - 1, 2 - a, 0)\\nPR = R - P = (a - 1, b - a, 3 - b)\\n\\nStep 2: For PQ and PR to be parallel, there must exist some scalar k such that each component of PQ equals k times the corresponding component of PR. This gives the system:\\n(1) a - 1 = k (a - 1)\\n(2) 2 - a = k (b - a)\\n(3) 0 = k (3 - b)\\n\\nStep 3: Consider equation (1):\\nIf a - 1 ≠ 0, then dividing both sides by (a - 1) yields k = 1.\\n\\nStep 4: Setting k = 1 in equation (3) gives 0 = 3 - b, so b = 3.\\nThen, equation (2) becomes 2 - a = b - a, i.e. 2 - a = 3 - a, which simplifies to 2 = 3, a contradiction.\\n\\nStep 5: Therefore, the assumption a - 1 ≠ 0 must be false. So, we must have a - 1 = 0, i.e. a = 1.\\n\\nStep 6: Substitute a = 1 into the points: P = (1, 1, b), Q = (1, 2, b) and R = (1, b, 3). Notice that all x-coordinates are 1, so the points are in a plane parallel to the y-z plane with fixed x.\\n\\nStep 7: Now, compute the vectors with a = 1:\\nPQ = (0, 2 - 1, b - b) = (0, 1, 0)\\nPR = (0, b - 1, 3 - b)\\n\\nFor these to be parallel, PR must be a scalar multiple of PQ. Since PQ = (0, 1, 0), PR must have a zero z-component. Thus, we require 3 - b = 0, so b = 3.\\n\\nStep 8: With a = 1 and b = 3, a + b = 1 + 3 = 4.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>4</answer>"
}

