  "final_answer": "<answer>2</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new policy is causing a lot of confusion among the employees at the office.; Did you hear that the new restaurant downtown has a secret menu item that's only accessible by solving a puzzle on their website?; The phrases '463', 'nitrogen', '463', 'positive telephone number', 'slash', and '947' within the statement; My favorite type of coffee is a medium‐roast cappuccino with a sprinkle of cinnamon on top; A. Dinev , K. Garov , N Belukhov</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Consider an infinite white plane divided into square cells. For which integer k is it possible to paint a finite (nonzero) set of cells black so that on each horizontal, vertical, and diagonal line (both main diagonals) the number of black cells is either 0 or exactly k?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Interpret the condition: We are to choose a finite set B of black cells on an infinite grid. For any straight line in one of four directions (horizontal, vertical, and the two diagonal directions), if the line contains any black cell (i.e. meets B), then it must contain exactly k black cells. Otherwise, it contains 0 black cells.\n2. Consider the simplest nonempty possibility. A single black cell: In this configuration, every line passing through that cell has exactly 1 black cell (because it is the only black cell on that line) and all lines not through it have 0. Hence the condition is satisfied with k = 1.\n3. Check possibility for k > 1. Suppose k > 1 and there exists a finite configuration B satisfying the condition. Pick any black cell b in B. Through b there are four lines (horizontal, vertical, and two diagonals). Each such line, by the condition, must contain exactly k black cells. Thus b must share its row with k - 1 other black cells, and similarly for the other three directions. Because B is finite, the black cells tend not to be arranged in a perfect complete pattern on all lines. In any arrangement with at least two black cells, many lines passing through a black cell would have only that one black cell unless additional cells are forced along that line. Constructing such a finite arrangement consistently for all four directions simultaneously (so that every line that meets B has exactly k black cells) turns out to be impossible, unless one uses the trivial configuration where B has a single cell (yielding k = 1). Many attempted constructions for k > 1 inevitably lead to lines that cross B in a number different from k.\n4. Conclusion: The only finite (nonempty) black cell configuration that meets the condition is the trivial case of a single black cell, which forces k = 1.\n5. Therefore, the answer is k = 1.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new policy at the coffee shop has led to a noticeable increase in the variety of biscotti flavors offered.\", \"Did you know that the shortest war in history was between Britain and Zanzibar on August 27, 1896, and lasted only 38 minutes?\", \"Did you hear that the new restaurant downtown has an all-you-can-eat sushi buffet on Fridays?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Consider all 5‐letter sequences formed (with repetitions allowed) from the set {T, U, R, N, I, P} arranged in lexicographic (dictionary) order. Two sequences are called anagrams of each other if one can be obtained by rearranging the letters of the other. How many pairs of anagrams (within the same anagram block) are there such that there are exactly 100 sequences between them in the dictionary order?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Notice that any two anagrams come from the same multiset (i.e. have exactly the same letters in some order). Moreover, when all sequences from a given multiset are arranged in lexicographic order, they appear consecutively as a block. Therefore, if two anagrams sitting in the same block have exactly 100 sequences between them, then their positions within that block differ by 101. \n2. Let M be the number of distinct anagrams (i.e. the size of the block) of a given multiset. For a pair with positions i and i+101 to exist, we require M ≥ 102, and for each block such pairs are counted by (M – 101). \n3. We must determine in which cases M ≥ 102. For a 5‐letter word from the set {T, U, R, N, I, P} (which has 6 elements) with repetition allowed, various multisets are possible. However, the maximum possible number of anagrams occurs when all letters are distinct because then M = 5! = 120. For any multiset that has repeated letters the number of distinguishable arrangements is smaller than 120. Since 120 ≥ 102 and all other possibilities yield M < 102, the only candidates for having pairs with a gap of 100 in between are those multisets where all five letters are distinct. \n4. Count the number of multisets with 5 distinct letters chosen from 6. That is C(6, 5) = 6. \n5. In each such block the number of anagrams is 120. The number of pairs that are exactly 101 positions apart (with 100 sequences between them) is 120 – 101 = 19 for each block. \n6. Therefore, the total number of pairs over all such blocks is 6 * 19 = 114.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>114</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The professor's favorite flavor of ice cream is rocky road.; Have you tried that new restaurant downtown that serves vegan sushi?; The weather in Paris is quite unpredictable during the spring season.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Given a regular decagon with vertices A₀, A₁, A₂, …, A₉, compute the measure of ∠A₀A₃A₇.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. In a regular decagon, the vertices lie on a circle and are equally spaced. Thus, the central angle between consecutive vertices is 360°/10 = 36°.\n2. The vertices have the following central angles: A₀ at 0°, A₃ at 3×36° = 108°, and A₇ at 7×36° = 252°.\n3. To determine the inscribed angle ∠A₀A₃A₇ (with vertex A₃), we need the measure of the intercepted arc from A₀ to A₇ that does not include A₃. Since going from A₀ (0°) to A₇ (252°) in the counterclockwise direction passes through 108° (A₃), we take the other arc: 360° − (252° − 0°) = 360° − 252° = 108°.\n4. The inscribed angle is half the measure of its intercepted arc, so ∠A₀A₃A₇ = 108°/2 = 54°.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>54°</answer>"
}

