{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new coffee shop downtown has the best croissants in the city, in my humble opinion.\", \"The new restaurant in town serves an amazing vegan quinoa bowl.\", \"I'm planning to try rock climbing for the first time this weekend, have you ever been?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Consider functions f : [0,1] → ℝ satisfying the conditions (i)–(iii) (with, for example, f(0)=0 and f(1)=1 as natural boundary conditions). Find the smallest constant c such that f(x) ≤ c·x for every function f satisfying (i)–(iii) and every x in [0,1].</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "We interpret the (i)–(iii) conditions as typical normalization and monotonicity or convexity-type conditions. In many such problems one assumes that f(0)=0 and f(1)=1. Under reasonable side conditions (for example, if f is also ‘well‐behaved’ so that the value f(x)/x is maximized by the linear function f(x)=x) one expects that the function attaining the maximum ratio is the linear one. For f(x)=x we have f(x)/x = 1 for all x > 0. Since any other function meeting the same boundary conditions and the additional restrictions cannot give a larger ratio (otherwise the conditions would be violated), the smallest constant c for which f(x) ≤ c·x for all x ∈ [0,1] must be 1.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The customer service representative listened attentively to the customer's concerns about the delayed package.; I'm planning a trip to the beach this summer to watch the sunset and collect seashells.; The new cafe on the corner is serving a delicious lavender latte this week.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find the number of nonempty families 𝒜 of subsets of {1, 2, …, 2014} satisfying: (a) For any subsets S₁, S₂ in 𝒜, the intersection S₁ ∩ S₂ is also in 𝒜; (b) If S is in 𝒜 and T ⊆ {1,2,…,2014} with S ⊆ T, then T is in 𝒜.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that the properties given (closure under intersection and upward closure) imply that the family is a filter on the set {1,2,…,2014}.\nStep 2: In a finite Boolean lattice every filter is principal; that is, there exists a unique minimal element m (which is the intersection of all members of the family) such that the filter is exactly {T ⊆ {1,2,…,2014} : m ⊆ T}.\nStep 3: Conversely, for every subset m ⊆ {1,2,…,2014}, the family defined by F₍ₘ₎ = {T ⊆ {1,2,…,2014} : m ⊆ T} is a valid filter (i.e., it satisfies both conditions).\nStep 4: Therefore, each subset m of {1,2,…,2014} uniquely determines a valid family. Since m can be any subset (including the empty set – note that if m = ∅ then F₍∅₎ = the entire power set, which indeed satisfies the conditions), the total number of such families is equal to the number of subsets of {1,2,…,2014}.\nStep 5: The number of subsets of a set with 2014 elements is 2^(2014).\nStep 6: Hence, the answer is 2^(2014).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2^(2014)</answer>"
}

